*\nLook at the denominator! As $t$ approaches $\\frac{1}{2x_0}$, the denominator goes to zero, meaning **$x(t)$ reaches infinity in a finite amount of time**. \nBecause the classical particle escapes the universe in finite time, the classical flow is \"incomplete.\" In quantum mechanics, this manifests as probability \"leaking\" out at infinity. If you solve the deficiency equations $S^\\dagger \\psi \u003d \\pm i \\psi$, you will find $L^2(\\mathbb{R})$ integrable solutions, meaning its deficiency indices are non-zero (specifically $(1,1)$). Therefore, it is **not essentially self-adjoint**.\n\n---\n\n### Question 1: $H \u003d p_y y (2x) + p_x y$\nNow let\u0027s apply the exact same logic to your 2D operator.\n\n**1. The Symmetric Operator:**\nWe want $S \u003d H + H^\\dagger$. \nUsing $p_x \u003d -i\\hbar \\partial_x$ and $p_y \u003d -i\\hbar \\partial_y$, let\u0027s write out $H$:\n$$ H \u003d -i\\hbar (2x \\partial_y y + y \\partial_x) \u003d -i\\hbar (2xy \\partial_y + 2x + y \\partial_x) $$\nNow, taking the adjoint $H^\\dagger$ (remembering that $(\\partial_y y)^\\dagger \u003d -y \\partial_y$):\n$$ H^\\dagger \u003d -i\\hbar (2xy \\partial_y + y \\partial_x) $$\nAdding them together, the symmetric operator is:\n$$ S \u003d H + H^\\dagger \u003d -i\\hbar \\left( 2y \\partial_x + 4xy \\partial_y + 2x \\right) $$\n\n**2. The Classical Flow:**\nThe derivative part gives us the 2D classical vector field $\\vec{v}(x,y) \u003d (2y, 4xy)$. The classical equations of motion are:\n1. $\\frac{dx}{dt} \u003d 2y$\n2. $\\frac{dy}{dt} \u003d 4xy$\n\nWe can find the path of the particle by dividing the two equations:\n$$ \\frac{dy}{dx} \u003d \\frac{4xy}{2y} \u003d 2x $$\nIntegrating this yields the trajectory shape: $y(x) \u003d C e^{x^2}$. \nNow substitute this back into the $\\frac{dx}{dt}$ equation to see how fast it travels along this path:\n$$ \\frac{dx}{dt} \u003d 2 C e^{x^2} $$\nTo find how long it takes for the particle to go from $x \u003d 0$ to $x \u003d \\infty$,