ty $$\nHere, the particle actually slows down as it gets further away. The time it takes to reach infinity diverges even faster than the previous cases (as a polynomial rather than a logarithm or linear function).\n\n---\n\n### The Golden Rule of Essential Self-Adjointness\nYou have just derived a fundamental theorem in quantum mechanics and dynamical systems! \n\nFor a smooth classical vector field (no poles) to be complete, **the vector field can grow no faster than linearly as it approaches infinity**. \n* If $f(x)$ grows like $x^1$ or slower ($x^0$, $x^{-1}$, etc.), the time integral diverges, the flow is complete, and the quantum operator is **essentially self-adjoint**.\n* If $f(x)$ grows like $x^2$ or faster (degree difference $\\ge 2$), the time integral converges (e.g., $\\int \\frac{dx}{x^2} \u003d -\\frac{1}{x} \\big|^\\infty \u003d 0$), the particle escapes in finite time, and the quantum operator is **NOT essentially self-adjoint**. \n\n*(Note: What if the particle approaches a point where $f(x) \u003d 0$? The velocity goes to zero, making it a \"fixed point.\" If you evaluate the integral approaching a zero, you\u0027ll find it also evaluates to $t \u003d \\infty$. The particle just slowly drifts toward a stop, meaning zeros in the numerator are perfectly safe and do not ruin completeness!)*",
