      "text": "Yes, there is a powerful and rigorous way to handle this without having to perform coordinate transformations or guess the \"right\" boundary conditions. \n\nThis approach relies on the **Method of Characteristics** (from the study of Partial Differential Equations) and the concept of the **Classical Flow**. Because your operator is first-order, it is fundamentally tied to the classical motion of particles.\n\nHere is the step-by-step rigorous framework to determine the evolution and the divergence time for any polynomial $f(x)$.\n\n---\n\n### 1. The Operator as a First-Order PDE\nThe Schrödinger equation $i\\hbar \\partial_t \\psi \u003d S\\psi$ with $S \u003d -i\\hbar(2f \\partial_x + f\u0027)$ is a first-order linear PDE:\n$$ \\partial_t \\psi + 2f(x) \\partial_x \\psi + f\u0027(x) \\psi \u003d 0 $$\nThis is a **transport equation** with a source term. The general solution is found using the **Method of Characteristics**.\n\n### 2. Rigorous Determination of the Divergence\nDefine the \"characteristic curve\" $x(t; x_0)$—the trajectory of a classical particle starting at $x_0$ at $t\u003d0$:\n$$ \\frac{dx}{dt} \u003d 2f(x), \\quad x(0) \u003d x_0 $$\nThe time of divergence $\\tau(x_0)$ is defined as the time it takes for $x(t)$ to reach the boundary of the domain (usually $\\pm \\infty$ for a polynomial). You find this rigorously by:\n$$ \\tau(x_0) \u003d \\int_{x_0}^{\\pm \\infty} \\frac{dx}{2f(x)} $$\n\n*   **If $\\tau(x_0) \u003d \\infty$:** The flow is complete. The operator is essentially self-adjoint.\n*   **If $\\tau(x_0) \u003c \\infty$:** The flow is incomplete. The wavepacket will \"hit\" the boundary at time $\\tau$.\n\n### 3. Rigorous Time-Evolution (The Propagator)\nYou don\u0027t need a coordinate transformation to write the solution; you can write it using the **flow map**. \n\nLet $\\Phi_t(x_0)$ be the solution to the ODE above (the position of a particle at time $t$ that started at $x_0$). The solution to the Schrödinger equation is