      "text": "Solving the ODE $\\frac{dx}{dt} \u003d 2f(x)$ for an arbitrary polynomial $f(x)$ is a classic problem in dynamical systems. While there isn\u0027t always a simple \"pencil and paper\" solution (like $x \u003d \\sin(t)$), there are three rigorous ways to solve it depending on what you need.\n\n---\n\n### 1. The Separation of Variables (The \"Exact\" Implicit Solution)\nSince the equation $\\frac{dx}{dt} \u003d 2f(x)$ is **separable**, you can always write the formal solution as an integral:\n\n$$\\int_{x_0}^{x} \\frac{du}{2f(u)} \u003d t$$\n\nIf $f(x)$ is a polynomial, the integral $\\int \\frac{du}{f(u)}$ is always solvable using **Partial Fraction Decomposition**.\n\n*   **Step A:** Factor $f(x)$ into its roots (real and complex): $f(x) \u003d c(x-r_1)(x-r_2)...(x-r_n)$.\n*   **Step B:** Decompose $\\frac{1}{f(u)}$ into a sum of simple fractions $\\frac{A_i}{u-r_i}$.\n*   **Step C:** Integrate. You will get terms involving $\\ln|x - r_i|$ (for real roots) or $\\arctan$ (for complex conjugate roots).\n\n**The Result:** You will end up with an expression like $G(x) - G(x_0) \u003d t$, where $G(x)$ is the antiderivative. This gives you $t$ as a function of $x$. **To get $x(t)$, you invert the function $G$.**\n\n---\n\n### 2. The Inversion Problem (Why we don\u0027t always need an explicit $x(t)$)\nYou might worry that you can\u0027t invert $G(x)$ to get $x(t)$ explicitly. **In physics, you often don\u0027t have to.** \n\nLook back at the Propagator formula from the previous step:\n$$\\psi(x, t) \u003d \\psi(\\Phi_{-t}(x), 0) \\cdot \\exp \\left( -\\int_0^t f\u0027(\\Phi_{s-t}(x)) \\, ds \\right)$$\n\nNotice that you only ever need to evaluate the flow at a specific point $x$ at time $t$. You can use the **Implicit Function Theorem**. If you have the equation $G(x) - G(x_0) \u003d t$, you can numerically solve for $x$ very efficiently using Newton’s Method or other root-finding algorithms. You don\u0027t need a closed-form formula for $x(t)$ to compute the time evolution of the wavepacket!\n\n---\n\n### 3. Numerical Integration (The \"Engineer\u0027s\" Rigorous Way)\nIf you are working with a high-degree polynomial (where finding roots is difficult), you use a numerical solver. Since you are solving $\\frac{dx}{dt} \u003d 2f(x)$, you are dealing with a **first-order autonomous ODE**. \n\nThese are extremely stable. A standard **Runge-Kutta (RK4)** method will solve this with incredibly high precision.\n\n**Why this is rigorous:**\nBecause $f(x)$ is a polynomial, it is **Lipschitz continuous** on any compact interval. This guarantees:\n1.  **Existence and Uniqueness:** A unique solution $\\Phi_t(x_0)$ exists for any starting point.\n2.  **Global Flow:** The solution exists as long as the particle doesn\u0027t hit a singularity or infinity.\n3.  **Error Bounds:** You can calculate the error of your numerical propagator precisely.\n\n---\n\n### Summary of the \"Workflow\"\nIf you are given $f(x) \u003d x^3 - x$:\n\n1.  **Partial Fractions:** $\\frac{1}{x^3-x} \u003d \\frac{1}{x-1} \\cdot \\frac{1}{x+1} \\cdot \\frac{1}{x} \u003d \\dots$\n2.  **Integrate:** You get $t \u003d \\frac{1}{2} \\ln \\left| \\frac{x-1}{x+1} \\right| + \\dots$ (the specific form).\n3.  **Analyze Divergence:** Look at where this expression blows up. As $x \\to 1$, $t \\to \\infty$. This tells you the divergence behavior without ever needing an explicit formula for $x(t)$.\n4.  **Propagate:** If you want to know where a wavepacket is at time $t$, you just solve the transcendental equation (from step 2) for $x$ using a root finder.\n\n**Crucial Insight:** You don\u0027t need $x(t)$ to be a pretty function of $t$. You only need to know that the map $x \\mapsto \\Phi_t(x)$ is a **diffeomorphism** of the domain. As long as you can numerically invert $G(x)$, you can compute the quantum evolution as accurately as you like!",
