    }, {
      "text": "When you move from one variable $x$ to multiple variables $\\mathbf{x} \u003d (x_1, x_2, \\dots, x_n)$, the operator takes the form of a **divergence-type operator** (or a first-order differential operator).\n\nIf your Hamiltonian is of the form $S \u003d \\sum_i (p_i f_i(\\mathbf{x}) + f_i(\\mathbf{x}) p_i)$, the classical flow is now a **vector field** $\\mathbf{V}(\\mathbf{x})$ defined by:\n$$\\frac{d\\mathbf{x}}{dt} \u003d 2\\mathbf{f}(\\mathbf{x}) \u003d 2(f_1, f_2, \\dots, f_n)$$\n\nThe rigor of the single-variable case holds, but the complexity increases because you are no longer solving a single ODE; you are solving a **system of coupled ODEs**.\n\n---\n\n### 1. The Multi-Variable Method of Characteristics\nThe Schrödinger equation becomes:\n$$i\\hbar \\partial_t \\psi \u003d -i\\hbar \\left( 2\\mathbf{f} \\cdot \\nabla + (\\nabla \\cdot \\mathbf{f}) \\right) \\psi$$\nThis is a first-order transport equation in $n$ dimensions. The rigorous time evolution is still defined by the **Flow Map** $\\Phi_t(\\mathbf{x}_0)$.\n\nThe propagator formula remains essentially the same:\n$$\\psi(\\mathbf{x}, t) \u003d \\psi(\\Phi_{-t}(\\mathbf{x}), 0) \\cdot \\exp \\left( -\\int_0^t (\\nabla \\cdot \\mathbf{f})(\\Phi_{s-t}(\\mathbf{x})) \\, ds \\right)$$\n\n### 2. The Rigorous Proof of Divergence\nIn 1D, you had a single integral to check for finiteness. In multiple dimensions, you must check the **Completeness of the Vector Field $\\mathbf{f}(\\mathbf{x})$**.\n\nThe system is essentially self-adjoint if and only if the flow $\\Phi_t(\\mathbf{x})$ is defined for all $t \\in \\mathbb{R}$ and all $\\mathbf{x} \\in \\mathbb{R}^n$. The divergence happens if there exists at least one trajectory $\\mathbf{x}(t)$ such that $\\|\\mathbf{x}(t)\\| \\to \\infty$ or hits a singularity in finite time.\n\n**How to prove it rigorously for systems:**\n*   **Lyapunov Functions:** Find a function $L(\\mathbf{x})$ such that $\\frac{dL}{dt} \u003d \\nabla L \\cdot \\mathbf{V} \\le C L(\\mathbf{x})$. If you can show $L$ doesn\u0027t blow up in finite time, the flow is complete.\n*   **Divergence Theorem:** If the vector field $\\mathbf{f}$ is \"incompressible\" ($\\nabla \\cdot \\mathbf{f} \u003d 0$), then the flow preserves volume (Liouville\u0027s Theorem). If the volume is preserved and the vector field doesn\u0027t grow \"too fast\" at infinity, the flow is often complete.\n\n### 3. The \"Gotcha\": Integrability\nIn 1D, every autonomous ODE $\\dot{x} \u003d 2f(x)$ is integrable. In multiple variables, this is **false**.\n\n*   **Integrable Systems:** If your system has $n$ independent conserved quantities (constants of motion) in involution, you can reduce the problem to 1D-like integrations (Action-Angle variables). You can solve these explicitly.\n*   **Chaotic/Non-Integrable Systems:** If your vector field is complex (e.g., the $H \u003d p_y y (2x) + p_x y$ example you gave earlier), the flow might be **chaotic**. \n    *   You cannot solve the ODEs by hand.\n    *   You cannot easily write a closed-form formula for the propagator.\n    *   **However, you can still prove divergence.** Even for chaotic flows, there are rigorous numerical or analytical methods (like **Poincaré sections** or bounding the **Lyapunov exponents**) to prove that trajectories escape to infinity in finite time.\n\n### 4. How to analyze it in practice\nIf you are working with an arbitrary multi-variable polynomial vector field:\n\n1.  **Check for \"Escape Directions\":** Look at the highest-degree terms of the polynomials $f_i(\\mathbf{x})$. If the radial component of the vector field $\\mathbf{V} \\cdot \\hat{\\mathbf{r}}$ grows like $r^k$ with $k \u003e 1$ as $r \\to \\infty$, the particle **will** escape to infinity in finite time (non-self-adjoint).\n2.  **Use Hamiltonian Mechanics:** Even if your quantum operator isn\u0027t self-adjoint, treat the classical vector field $\\dot{\\mathbf{x}} \u003d 2\\mathbf{f}$ as a classical dynamical system.\n3.  **Numerical Flow:** Use a 4th-order Runge-Kutta integrator to track a \"cloud\" of points. If the cloud reaches a coordinate $x_i \\to \\infty$ while $t \u003c \\infty$, your operator is not essentially self-adjoint.\n\n### Summary of the difference\n| Feature | 1D Case | Multi-Variable Case |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Solving ODE** | Always integrable ($\\int dx/f$) | Usually non-integrable (Chaotic) |\n| **Divergence Test** | Integral converges | Lyapunov stability / Radial growth bounds |\n| **Flow** | Monotonic | Can be complex, mixing, or chaotic |\n| **Self-Adjointness** | Determined by boundary behavior | Determined by global flow completeness |\n\n**The rigorous bottom line:** To prove divergence in multiple variables, you don\u0027t need to solve the ODE explicitly. You only need to prove that there exists at least one trajectory $\\mathbf{x}(t)$ that escapes any compact set in finite time. For polynomials, this is usually determined by the **dominant terms at infinity** (the \"asymptotic vector field\").",
