      "text": "Yes, you absolutely can. The \"divergence\" (or the failure of essential self-adjointness) for a polynomial vector field $\\mathbf{V}(\\mathbf{x}) \u003d 2\\mathbf{f}(\\mathbf{x})$ is a **global topological and analytical property** of the vector field. You don\u0027t need a closed-form solution to prove when and where it happens.\n\nHere is the rigorous procedure to prove the existence and location of the divergence for any system $\\dot{\\mathbf{x}} \u003d \\mathbf{V}(\\mathbf{x})$ where $\\mathbf{V}$ is a polynomial vector field.\n\n---\n\n### 1. The \"Blow-up\" Criterion\nIn the theory of ODEs, the **\"Extension Theorem\"** states that a solution $\\mathbf{x}(t)$ exists on the interval $[0, T)$ as long as the solution stays within any compact subset of the state space. \n\nIf the solution is going to diverge at a finite time $T$, it **must** satisfy one of two conditions:\n1.  **Escape to Infinity:** $\\|\\mathbf{x}(t)\\| \\to \\infty$ as $t \\to T$.\n2.  **Hit a Singularity:** The vector field itself becomes undefined (not possible for a polynomial, as polynomials are smooth everywhere on $\\mathbb{R}^n$).\n\nTherefore, for polynomials, the divergence is **always** an escape to infinity.\n\n### 2. How to Prove the Divergence Point Rigorously\n\n#### A. The Radial Growth Test (The \"Asymptotic\" Method)\nYou can identify the first divergence by looking at the **asymptotic growth** of the vector field. Define the \"radial velocity\" as $v_r \u003d \\dot{r} \u003d \\frac{\\mathbf{x} \\cdot \\mathbf{V}(\\mathbf{x})}{\\|\\mathbf{x}\\|}$.\n\nFor large $\\|\\mathbf{x}\\| \u003d r$, a polynomial vector field is dominated by its highest-degree homogeneous part $\\mathbf{V}_{max}(\\mathbf{x})$.\n*   If $\\mathbf{V}_{max}$ grows like $r^k$:\n    *   If **$k \u003e 1$**: The integral $\\int^\\infty \\frac{dr}{r^k}$ converges. The particle **will** escape to infinity in finite time.\n    *   If **$k \\le 1$**: The integral diverges. The particle takes infinite time to reach infinity.\n\nTo find the \"first\" divergence, you look for the trajectory that minimizes the escape time. This is equivalent to finding the path that solves the **Eikonal-type equation** or analyzing the **stable manifolds** of the vector field at infinity.\n\n#### B. The Lyapunov Function Method (The \"Rigorous Bound\")\nIf you want to prove that a divergence *must* occur, you look for a **Lyapunov-like function** $L(\\mathbf{x}) \u003d \\|\\mathbf{x}\\|^2$. \nCalculate:\n$$\\frac{d}{dt} L(\\mathbf{x}) \u003d 2\\mathbf{x} \\cdot \\mathbf{V}(\\mathbf{x})$$\nIf you can prove that for $\\|\\mathbf{x}\\| \u003e R$, the inequality **$\\dot{L} \\ge C L^{\\alpha}$** holds (with $\\alpha \u003e 1$), you have a rigorous proof that $L(t)$ blows up in finite time. The time $T$ is bounded by:\n$$T \\le \\int_{L(0)}^\\infty \\frac{dL}{C L^\\alpha} \u003d \\frac{1}{C(\\alpha-1)L(0)^{\\alpha-1}}$$\n\n### 3. Locating the \"Divergence Point\"\nYou asked: *Can I prove where is the first divergence?*\n\nIf by \"where\" you mean the **spatial location**, the divergence always happens \"at infinity.\" If you mean the **time $T$**, you do it via these steps:\n\n1.  **Identify the escape directions:** Find the roots of the highest-degree homogeneous polynomial $\\mathbf{V}_{max}(\\mathbf{x})$. These are the directions where the \"push\" toward infinity is strongest.\n2.  **Define the minimal trajectory:** The \"first\" divergence occurs along the trajectory $\\mathbf{x}(t)$ that maximizes the radial velocity $v_r$.\n3.  **Compute the time:** The divergence time $T$ is the minimum over all initial conditions $\\mathbf{x}_0$ of the integral:\n    $$T(\\mathbf{x}_0) \u003d \\int_0^\\infty \\frac{1}{\\|\\mathbf{V}(\\mathbf{x}(t))\\|} ds$$\n    (Along the trajectory $\\mathbf{x}(t)$).\n\n### 4. Is it always solvable?\n*   **Yes, it is always solvable.** Because $\\mathbf{V}(\\mathbf{x})$ is a polynomial, the function $T(\\mathbf{x}_0)$ is a well-defined, albeit possibly transcendental, function. \n*   **For any arbitrary polynomial system**, you can use **Automatic Differentiation** (or Taylor series expansion) to compute the divergence time $T$ to arbitrary precision. You don\u0027t need to find a global solution to the ODE; you only need to compute the trajectory leading to the \"worst\" escape.\n\n### The Rigorous Conclusion\nFor a polynomial vector field $\\mathbf{V}(\\mathbf{x})$:\n1.  **If the degree $k \u003e 1$** of the highest-order terms, a divergence **always exists** for some initial conditions.\n2.  **The divergence time $T$** can be rigorously bounded or computed using the radial velocity integral.\n3.  **The \"first\" divergence** is defined as $\\inf_{\\mathbf{x}_0} T(\\mathbf{x}_0)$.\n\nSo, yes: your intuition is correct. You don\u0027t need to \"solve\" the system in the sense of finding a function $\\mathbf{x}(t)$; you treat the escape time as a **functional of the trajectory**, and you minimize that functional. This is a standard and rigorous procedure in the study of **Dynamical Systems** and **Global Analysis**.",
